Kubernetes on Raspberry Pi, The Hard Way - Part 1
Now the fun begins&hellip;
After the setup of the raspberry pi servers in part 1, I have the hostnames and IPs in the table below. We now have to create a CA and certificates for all the different pieces of the cluster. Then create kubeconfigs for the different components to use to connect to the cluster, and distribute everything out to the nodes.

I have encountered this problem numerous times, and every time I am told &ldquo;There is something wrong with the network!!&rdquo;
What I really need is someone much more creative than me to write a children&rsquo;s song similar to Schoolhouse Rock&rsquo;s &ldquo;I&rsquo;m Just a Bill&rdquo;, except for network packets
Scenario    There are 2 servers. Each server has 2 network interfaces that all have listening addresses in separate subnets. The Default route for each server is via eth0.
